**November Is Where Two Paths Converge — The Fall Progress Check and Goal-Setting Groundwork Your Board Needs This Month**

November 9, 2027

---

October is behind you. Your board held its first full data review of the fall. You made written decisions on each goal — accept trajectory, direct change, or request more information. You published a community summary. You calendared a November check-in for every directed change.

Or your board entered October without adopted goals. You spent October gathering baseline data instead. You tracked two or three metrics. You documented what you learned. You did not set targets yet — you built the foundation that makes January goals credible.

Either way, November is where both paths converge.

November is the last full board meeting before the December year-end governance reset. And November is the month where the board delivers on the commitments October created — whether those commitments were directed changes on adopted goals or baseline data that becomes a draft goal set.

Here is what November requires from your board, regardless of which track you are on.

---

**Track one — For boards with adopted goals: The fall progress check**

If your board made directed changes at the October data review, November is where you find out whether those changes are working.

The October arc kickoff described November as the first full check-in after the data review. The superintendent reports on implementation of the October directed changes. The board reviews the results. The board confirms the trajectory or adjusts.

Here is the specific protocol for that check-in.

The board president places one item on the November agenda: "Progress check on October directed changes — fifteen minutes." The item covers each goal that received a directed change at the October data review. For each goal, the superintendent answers three questions.

First, what action was taken since the October data review?

Second, what preliminary result does the November data show?

Third, is the trajectory moving toward the goal target or away from it?

The board does not need a full data review for this check-in. Full data reviews happen quarterly. November is a pulse check. The board needs enough information to answer one question: did the October directed change produce movement in the right direction? If yes, the board confirms the trajectory and the superintendent continues executing. If no, the board adjusts — either the strategy or the expectation.

But the November check-in serves a second purpose that is just as important as the progress review.

November is the last full board meeting before the December year-end governance reset. That means November is the month to surface any governance issues that need attention before the board evaluates its annual performance and opens the 2028 cycle.

Here is the question every board with adopted goals should answer at its November meeting: *What does this board need to resolve before the December reset?*

If the board-superintendent partnership has shown strain since October's budget pressure built, November is the time to address it — not December, when the board is trying to close the year and preview the next one.

If the board's September self-evaluation identified improvement priorities that have not been addressed, November is the time to ask why.

If a governance pattern — meeting time management, committee effectiveness, board member preparation — has been eroding since the fall began, November is the month to fix it before it becomes normalized.

I have watched boards in **Hazelwood (MO)** handle this well. At every November meeting, they schedule a forty-five-minute governance health check. It is a structured review in three parts.

Part one — board functioning. Are board meetings producing governance outcomes or just filling time? Are board members prepared? Are board members staying in the governance lane?

Part two — meeting effectiveness. Is the agenda producing decisions or just conversation? Are the data reviews producing written decisions or just reports received? Is the board covering too many items or too few?

Part three — partnership quality. Is the board-superintendent relationship producing trust or eroding it? Are there issues that need to be addressed before they become problems? Is the board communicating clearly with the superintendent and the superintendent communicating clearly with the board?

The Hazelwood governance health check is not a formal evaluation. It is a fifteen-minute board discussion — forty-five minutes total with setup and close — that prevents small issues from becoming December problems.

The boards I have coached that use this format consistently report that the November health check surfaces two or three issues every year that would have been left unaddressed until they became urgent. And addressing those issues in November means the board walks into the December reset cleaner than it would have otherwise.

---

**Track two — For boards without adopted goals: The goal-setting groundwork**

If your board entered the fall without adopted goals, November is the month where the baseline-gathering quarter you started in October produces its first concrete output.

The September goal clarity piece described the baseline quarter framework — October through December is the window where the board does not set targets but collects data. The board selects two to three metrics. The board tracks one data point per month for each metric. The board documents what it learns in a one-page note per metric. By December, the board has enough data to draft credible goals for January adoption.

November is the midpoint of that baseline quarter. And November is the month where the board shifts from data collection to goal drafting.

The superintendent should present a draft goal set to the board at the November meeting. The draft should include three to five goals, each with a specific metric, baseline data from October's review, a proposed target, and a timeline for community input before formal adoption in January.

The draft does not need to be final. November is not the month for adoption. November is the month for the board to see the draft, discuss it, and give direction to the superintendent before the December meeting where the board will finalize the goal language and set the January adoption timeline.

Here is what the November discussion on draft goals should produce. Four outcomes.

First, the board confirms the metrics. Are these the right two to five metrics? Do they represent the board's highest priorities? Do they reflect what the community expects the board to be focused on? The board does not need to commit to final language. The board needs to give the superintendent a clear direction on which metrics to develop further.

Second, the board reviews the baseline data. The October data review produced the first data point. The board should understand where the district is starting from for each metric. The baseline data gives the January goal-setting process its credibility. A target without a starting point is not a target. It is a wish.

Third, the board discusses the proposed targets. Are they ambitious enough? Are they realistic given the baseline data? The board does not need to agree on targets in November. The board needs to have the conversation that surfaces the tension between ambition and realism — because that tension is what produces good goal language.

Fourth, the board sets the community input timeline. The superintendent should present a plan for community input on the draft goals before January adoption. The plan should include a timeline — December through early January — and a format — a board meeting presentation, a community survey, a work session with stakeholder groups.

A board that produces these four outcomes at its November meeting enters December with a draft goal set, board direction on metrics and targets, and a community input timeline. That board will adopt goals in January with real data behind every goal and real community engagement in the process.

A board that shows up in November without a superintendent draft, without a baseline data set, and without a community input timeline will spend December scrambling to produce what it should have produced in October.

The baseline quarter framework works only if the board executes each month. October was data collection. November is goal drafting. December is goal finalization and community input. January is adoption. Skipping November does not accelerate the timeline — it compresses the quality out of the goals.

---

**What both tracks produce for December**

Here is the convergence point.

Whether your board enters November on track one or track two, November produces the foundation for the December year-end governance reset.

For boards with adopted goals, November produces:
- A progress check on October directed changes — confirming or adjusting trajectory
- A governance health check that surfaces issues before the year-end reset
- A clear picture of what the board needs to resolve before December

For boards without adopted goals, November produces:
- A draft goal set with baseline data and proposed targets
- Board direction on metrics, ambition level, and community input timeline
- A path to formal adoption in January

Both paths lead to December. And December is where the governance cycle closes and the next one opens.

The December reset piece — publishing December 7 — will cover the year-end governance review, the superintendent evaluation kickoff, the January organizational meeting preparation, and the 2028 goal-setting preview. November's work feeds directly into that reset.

A board that executes November well walks into December with momentum. A board that lets November slip will spend December catching up instead of closing the year.

The November meeting is not the end of the fall governance cycle. It is the hinge. The quality of your board's November meeting will determine the quality of your board's December reset. And the quality of your December reset will determine whether your board starts January governing or starts January recovering.

